INSERT INTO `phpbb_privmsgs_text` VALUES (2356,'2a1ddcdcd7','Hey this is what I asked Harold.  Maybe you could comment on this matter as well Mr. Meadmaker!  \r\n\r\n\"Harold, I have been researching onions again for the experimental onion beer.  It is really neat stuff actually.  I am leaning toward dry hopping persae with onions to not destroy overall beer.  With that being said, I have found through research that soaking chopped onions in acetic acid help ward off the sulfuric acid that would be produced through the cutting process.  My question is how much acetic acid does it take to create negative affects to the environment inside the fermenter and the beer?  Also at that stage in fermenting is it possible that the acidity of the soaked onion would stop ferementation?  Do you think it would be better to wait and add at say tertiary fermentation?  Keep in mind I am not trying overpower the beer, just lend subtle hints to give the simple aroma and slight flavor of onion.  Any advice would be greatly appreciated.\"\r\n\r\nI know there are networks of cellulose matrixes which give the overall structure to the onion; and there subnetworks that generate the liquid inside of each matrix which when cut produces the sulfonic acids.  When the sulfonic acids come in contact with water, it sulfuric acid is produced.  Carl thought of soaking an onion in vodka and just pouring said liquor into the fermenter.  What do you think about the acetic acid?  How do your meads react to the citric acid you add?  Citric and acetic acid are similar in acidity.  \r\n\r\nThanks man,\r\n\r\n :devil:');
