INSERT INTO `phpbb_privmsgs_text` VALUES (5075,'e925227808','The \"average\" South Carolina NG regulator has 7\" of pressure that can handle up to 375,000 BTU\'s.  They can upgrade this possibly easily to 2lbs or 5lbs by switching/adding regulators.  I assume my furnace is about 125,000 and 100,000BTU, this leaves 150,000 BTU to play with for grill/hotwater/pool heater/etc.  My furnace in Lynchburg was 365,000 BTU so my estimates could be totally off....\r\n\r\nPart of this is a comparison of apples and oranges- like pressure and drilling out your thingy.\r\n\r\nOur Natural Gas is supplied with a regulator that controls both a) flow rate (cubic feet per hour) and b) pressure.  While we can manipulate these independently they are not totally independent.  You can control the flow rate by drilling out your burner thingy but can not control the pressure.  \r\n\r\nSo the first step is what devices are hooked up to the NG.  In my case it is both furnaces and that is it. You need to calculate the total \"load\" on your system.  For example lets say you have:\r\n\r\n125,000 BTU gaspack/furnace for lower zone\r\n50,000 BTU hot water heater\r\n100,000 BTU grill\r\n60,000 BTU stove\r\n40,000 BTU pool heater\r\n\r\nTotal load 375,000-   this means you can\'t hook up anything else (or you can\'t use it all at same time otherwise perhaps kaboom!)\r\n\r\nor perhaps you don\'t have a stove or pool heater (I don\'t know what you have...) so your total load will be 275,000 and your available BTU\'s will be 100,000.  \r\n\r\nThen step 2 is to see the max BTU your burner can handle.  In my case I think it is like 150,000 BTU.  I think I run my burner at closer to 80,000 BTU though.  The reason for this is to make sure I don\'t supply too much gas to my burner.\r\n\r\nStep 3-  I know I have available 100,000BTU at 7\" of pressure so then I can determine the size of whole I need to drill to equal that.  If perhaps my burner could only handle 65,000 BTU-   then even though I have 100,000 BTU available I would drill my hole to handle 65,000 BTU at 7\" of pressure.\r\n\r\nnotes to self:\r\n\r\nNG available at 2lbs (610,000 BTU) and 5lbs.  To do this they set up multible regulators-   one to allow 610 cubic feet to house- then another to bring down pressure to 7\".  this is like the multible regulator in a kegorator-   set first \"master\" to say 30 PSI to allow for max pressure (high flow regulator at that) then the others set at 7psi (1.5volume)up to 15psi (3 volume) depending on what needs are.\r\n\r\nThey (SCEG?) pays for 1st regulator-  we pay for rest I assume ~100 but this is only assumption-   could be like propane- $20 or Medical O2- $300.\r\n\r\ncan estimate BTU (or CFH) by running one device and watching meter.  \r\n\r\n1000BTU= 1Cubic Foot of NG\r\n1Gallon of propane=91,600 BTU\r\n1 Pound Propane = 21,500 BTU\r\n1 CF = 7.48 gallons\r\n685,168 BTU in 1 CF of propane');
