INSERT INTO `phpbb_privmsgs_text` VALUES (3454,'12940bf6d1','[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]I dont understand why others feel they are entitled to it for free.[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nIt wouldn\'t be free. It would not be a charity. It would be paid through taxes, just as fire departments, roads, and any other government services are.\r\n\r\n[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]communities find desirable and are willing to pay for indirectly[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nThat\'s my whole point. I\'m not making a direct comparison between a police force and universal healthcare -- I\'m just saying that to many people, it would fall under the category of those services that we believe the government should provide to the people, paid for by taxes. Look, it obviously comes down to a difference of opinion. Most people agree that the government has the right to levy taxes in order to pay for certain programs and services. Some people simply feel that universal healthcare should be included there, because they feel it\'s the right thing to do. I understand that not everyone feels that way. It\'s a difference of opinion, or philosophy, or whatever you want to say.\r\n\r\n[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]Ill look further into your claim that malpractice insurance is not a factor but I would think that even a small reduction in premiums that could be passed on to the consumer is a good thing.[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nIt\'s not my claim. It\'s the government\'s, and the insurance companies\' themselves. It\'s just a very, very small component of the overall cost of health care. I\'m not going to argue with the assertion that tort reform, in some cases, may indeed be advisable. I\'m just not going to believe that tort reform will solve our health care issues, nor will it even play a major role.\r\n\r\n\r\n[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]Those with insurance have to pay in the form of lower wages, premiums and deductibles.[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nSo I guess you\'ll agree that already, people are paying indirectly for other people\'s health care to a degree.\r\n\r\n[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]If the government takes over the healthcare (socialized medicine) then there will be less accountability[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nLess accountability to shareholders. I agree.\r\n\r\n[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]higher costs[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nWhat about savings by removing profit?\r\n\r\n[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]less research (no profit motive), shortage of providers (no profit motive)[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nHere I would argue that the same motivation that would bring about universal health care in the first place (that it\'s the right thing to do, in order to help people) would encourage continued research and availability of services. And I happen not to believe that the motivation to make a profit is always what brings out the best in people, or companies. \r\n\r\n[quote:12940bf6d1=\"Pete Goodwin\"]I dont think it is a good thing and frankly I feel slighted that you would imply I think otherwise.[/quote:12940bf6d1]\r\n\r\nSorry, I didn\'t mean to slight you. But I will maintain that one can\'t simultaneously say that not having health coverage is a bad thing, and yet defend and wish to perpetuate a system where millions, inevitably, will not have health coverage. I\'m sorry, I just don\'t see those positions as being compatible.\r\n\r\nEven if people who earn minimum wage [i:12940bf6d1]could[/i:12940bf6d1] afford to purchase their own coverage privately, it would be so limited as to be almost useless. I have a friend who does this. Basically the only purpose her coverage serves is to keep her family from going bankrupt should something truly catastrophic happen to her. That\'s not exactly what I\'d call comprehensive health coverage.\r\n\r\nLike I said, some pretty big differences of opinion here. I can deal with that. My original intention was simply to put forth some facts and data, because it\'s when people can\'t agree on facts that really gets my goat.\r\n\r\nCheers,\r\n\r\nbp');
