INSERT INTO `phpbb_privmsgs_text` VALUES (3742,'86d80b37ac','Nice.\r\n\r\nYes, yellow was the original. I was out at the AHA conference in Portland when the Glatt mill was first introduced. Of course, there were dozens of homebrewers screaming \"how can I get one?\". The original was painted with Krylon spray paint. They said the production ones would be \"powder coated\". So, that is the way it came. The original rollers were slotted (I think), but when I ordered mine, they had changed the design to knurled rollers. The first time I used it by hand cranking, things were cool. I then motorized it, loaded it up with grain, and watched the grist throughput go to nothing. What happened is the diamond knurling filled up with flour and the small diameter rollers were too smooth to pull any grain through. I called Glatt, they said those rollers were an experiment and they would change out my rollers to the original slotted design. Sent the mill back, they returned it with slotted rollers plus the original knurled rollers. I think it was maybe a year later that they started constructing the chassis out of stainless steel.\r\n\r\nI found the original rollers, along with the note from Greg Glatt. They were replaced in May 1994, plus he put in updated gears. Wow, has it really been 13 years???????');
