INSERT INTO `phpbb_privmsgs_text` VALUES (3191,'6d3eebf319','Sure, I\'ll sell any combination of stuff. Let me know what you want, and you can return what you don\'t.  As far as the drippy faucet, I can take it back to see if I can figure out what is causing the drip. It could be as simple as tightening the nut on the back of the slider to push out the O-ring some more, or it might be solved by putting some silicone grease (keg lube) on the O-ring. I have never seen replacement O-rings for faucets, but I can do a search. I have a Dremel tool, so it wouldn\'t be too bad to polish the inside mating surface.\r\n\r\nI would at least put some drip trays under your faucets to catch any drips anyway. The (really) cheap way would to get one of those window planters from a garden center and either set it on the floor or come up with a way to mount it on the fridge. Or spread a towel to catch the drips.\r\n\r\nOne note on mounting the shanks. Depending on what is used as insulation in the refrigerator, you may have to cut a larger hole inside so you can tighten the shank properly to the wall. If the wall is filled with fiberglass, it doesn\'t have the rigidity to really tighten down the mounting nut. In that case, the 3 inch shanks would probably work since the nut doesn\'t tighten on the inside plastic panel. This assumes you are putting the faucets on the door. The side walls are usually steel and won\'t flex as much as plastic when tightening.');
